data.content:
Yes — the direct cast will throw `InvalidCastException` on failure, which obscures the test intent. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This gives a clear failure message ("Expected type EmailHandler, got …") rather than an unhandled exception. The generic overload `IsInstanceOfType<T>` is available in MSTest v3+; for older versions use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))`.
